00:15:55.250 --> 00:15:58.540
But there is one thing
you should keep in mind.

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:02.880
Since we have the
beam splitter here--

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:04.260
this is the correct answer.

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:06.790
But I want to point out
one subtlety for you, which

00:16:06.790 --> 00:16:08.900
will become important later.

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:12.530
The beam splitter has an
open part with the vacuum.

00:16:12.530 --> 00:16:16.800
And so when you said we can
measure before or by sort

00:16:16.800 --> 00:16:19.950
of just combining the two
beams with a big photodiode,

00:16:19.950 --> 00:16:25.730
we can measure after, that's
now a question for you-- which,

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:27.740
maybe hold the thought
and ask me later,

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:30.360
if it doesn't become clear
with the following question.

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:33.650
Hasn't the vacuum entered here,
and hasn't the vacuum, which

00:16:33.650 --> 00:16:36.206
has entered here
added fluctuations?

00:16:36.206 --> 00:16:37.580
So if you put in
a beam splitter,

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:41.610
and we mix in the vacuum
with our coherent states,

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:43.697
shouldn't that possibly
mean that if you

00:16:43.697 --> 00:16:47.060
use a big photodiode and
measure everything together,

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:49.750
that we measure the
variance we had before.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:52.150
But isn't that
possibly a contribution

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:55.470
of the vacuum, because we were
opening the door to the vacuum?

00:16:55.470 --> 00:16:56.530
Please hold the thought.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:02.720
OK.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:07.770
The next thing is now, you can't
have the solution that we take

00:17:07.770 --> 00:17:10.390
sort of a big photodiode
and combine the two beams,

00:17:10.390 --> 00:17:12.500
because I'm asking
you now is, what

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:17.069
is the variance in i1 minus i2?

00:17:17.069 --> 00:17:19.960
So you subtract
the two currents.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:22.950
So the question is, if
you have technical noise,

00:17:22.950 --> 00:17:24.920
the two beams would
be fluctuating,

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:27.170
and you would form i1 minus i2.

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:30.890
All the technical noise
would cancel away.

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:33.520
But what is shot noise?

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:35.770
Is shot noise technical noise?

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:39.710
Is shot noise that every
time you prepare an ensemble,

00:17:39.710 --> 00:17:44.190
there is a hiccup, and you
can split it and subtract it?

00:17:44.190 --> 00:17:46.230
So now, it's getting
really interesting.

00:17:46.230 --> 00:17:50.420
To what extent does a
beam splitter-- does

00:17:50.420 --> 00:17:52.990
a split coherent state,
which has shot noise,

00:17:52.990 --> 00:17:55.520
and you now perform the
difference of the measurement,

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:57.730
can you get rid of some
of the shot noise or not?

00:18:02.037 --> 00:18:02.745
You vote, please.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:21.180
Yes.

00:18:23.950 --> 00:18:28.310
So it doesn't matter
whether we measure

00:18:28.310 --> 00:18:30.000
the sum or the difference.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.820
So it seems, we have two beams.

00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:38.860
And it seems that the
noise in i1 and i2

00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:40.859
is completely uncorrelated.

00:18:40.859 --> 00:18:42.900
And whether we perform
the sum or the difference,

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:43.650
it doesn't matter.

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:48.690
As long as you think
about classical states

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:51.850
and coherent states, you can
get away with this notion.

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:54.530
But now I'm going to
add some squeezed light.

00:18:54.530 --> 00:18:57.131
And now, it's
getting more subtle.

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:03.540
So we have exactly
the same situation.

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:05.150
We have our beam splitter.

00:19:05.150 --> 00:19:11.640
We split our coherent beam into
two beams, exactly as before.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:15.110
But now, I'm playing
with a vacuum.

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:18.700
I'm playing with the open
part of the beam splitter,

00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:24.650
and I put in squeezed vacuum.

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:28.010
And just to be specific,
I've squeezed the vacuum

00:19:28.010 --> 00:19:31.340
in such a way that
what is narrow now

00:19:31.340 --> 00:19:35.930
is the quadrature component
of the coherent state.

00:19:35.930 --> 00:19:39.680
In other words, the coherent
state is cosine omega t.

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:42.050
In sine omega t, we haven't
been put in any photons.

00:19:42.050 --> 00:19:44.685
Our coherent state has really
a classical oscillation

00:19:44.685 --> 00:19:46.880
in cosine omega t.

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:50.480
And what I have squeezed
here with the vacuum

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:54.880
is the noise in the cosine
omega t quadrature component.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:20:00.000
So in other words, the coherent
state and the short axis

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.210
of the ellipse are the
same quadrature component,

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:08.020
which means, they
can now interfere.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:10.380
So the question is
now the following.

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:11.710
We split the beam.

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:14.060
We have n/2 photons here.

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:17.797
We have n/2 photons there.

00:20:17.797 --> 00:20:19.630
And what is now the
result for the variance?

00:20:23.056 --> 00:20:25.300
I formulated a
condition up there,

00:20:25.300 --> 00:20:30.240
which is the strong local
oscillator condition.

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:32.280
You should assume,
if you get confused,

00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:35.410
that the local oscillator
is very, very strong.

00:20:35.410 --> 00:20:38.370
And if you have any doubts
about some smaller terms,

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:40.880
just crank up the
power and make sure

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:43.980
that it's really the local
oscillator which dominates,

00:20:43.980 --> 00:20:47.881
which is the biggest
number in all equations.

00:20:47.881 --> 00:20:48.380
OK.

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:52.840
So the reference is
without squeezing,

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:57.530
the noise, or the
variance, in i1 was n/2.

00:20:57.530 --> 00:21:01.510
With n/2 photons, Poissonian
statistics was n/2.

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:08.230
The question is now, when
we use squeezed light,

00:21:08.230 --> 00:21:10.770
does the variance stay the same?

00:21:10.770 --> 00:21:12.010
Does it go up?

00:21:12.010 --> 00:21:13.850
Does it go down?

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:15.210
Or does it go to 0?

