00:32:14.360 --> 00:32:16.520
And this goes as follows.

00:32:16.520 --> 00:32:19.110
When you have a
coherent input, you

00:32:19.110 --> 00:32:23.480
can say you have a
deterministic classical field.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:28.180
And then, you have some noise
in one quadrature component,

00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:30.730
which is cosine omega t.

00:32:30.730 --> 00:32:32.710
And the i is a reminder
that there's also

00:32:32.710 --> 00:32:34.450
noise in sine omega t.

00:32:34.450 --> 00:32:37.750
So you can really say
the electric field has

00:32:37.750 --> 00:32:39.520
a sharp value,
but then, there is

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:42.529
some fluctuation in the
coefficient of cosine omega t

00:32:42.529 --> 00:32:45.070
and a little bit fluctuation in
the coefficient of sine omega

00:32:45.070 --> 00:32:46.720
t.

00:32:46.720 --> 00:32:51.140
And what is important now is, if
you shine that on a photodiode,

00:32:51.140 --> 00:32:52.330
this is sort of the field.

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:58.962
The current is proportional
to the square of it.

00:32:58.962 --> 00:33:00.670
You have to be a little
bit careful where

00:33:00.670 --> 00:33:03.920
you put complex conjugation,
but it is the square of it.

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:11.190
And now, if we use the strong
local oscillator assumption,

00:33:11.190 --> 00:33:13.260
we only take alpha
squared, which

00:33:13.260 --> 00:33:14.940
gives us a number of photons.

00:33:14.940 --> 00:33:18.160
But then, those
fluctuations are homodyned.

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:19.845
We only take-- we
don't consider that

00:33:19.845 --> 00:33:21.330
the square of the fluctuation.

00:33:21.330 --> 00:33:22.590
We only homodyne it.

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:28.350
We use, at the cross term,
where we multiply with alpha.

00:33:28.350 --> 00:33:36.380
So if I now put in
photon numbers for alpha,

00:33:36.380 --> 00:33:37.540
we get n photons.

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:38.690
Yes, OK.

00:33:38.690 --> 00:33:41.500
And now, we get some noise.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:47.190
Well, the noise is
the current squared.

00:33:47.190 --> 00:33:53.710
The noise is-- we take the
average of the current squared

00:33:53.710 --> 00:33:58.600
and subtract the average
of the current squared.

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:02.920
So if you do that--
this is the current

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:05.625
squared-- the current
squared average,

00:34:05.625 --> 00:34:08.690
and the average current
squared takes that away.

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:11.400
So we get this here
as the variance.

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:14.810
And now, I have to tell you that
in the units I'm using here,

00:34:14.810 --> 00:34:18.540
this delta a1 squared
for coherent state--

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:20.580
so if I show the
standard circle--

00:34:20.580 --> 00:34:22.570
the standard
Heisenberg uncertainty

00:34:22.570 --> 00:34:26.045
circle-- this quantity is 1/4.

00:34:26.045 --> 00:34:28.250
I've just kept track
of my constant.

00:34:28.250 --> 00:34:35.290
So therefore, we obtain in this
picture that the variance is n.

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:38.199
And this is Poissonian
light with a coherent state.

00:34:38.199 --> 00:34:41.679
And the fluctuation
squared of the current, n,

00:34:41.679 --> 00:34:43.900
this is Poissonian
statistics, square root

00:34:43.900 --> 00:34:45.530
in fluctuations of the current.

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:47.340
The variance is n.

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:49.989
But what you should
realize is one thing.

00:34:49.989 --> 00:34:53.409
The moment I have a
strong coherent state,

00:34:53.409 --> 00:34:57.190
the sign quadrature component
doesn't matter at all.

00:34:57.190 --> 00:34:59.740
Because if you multiply
cosine with sine and average,

00:34:59.740 --> 00:35:00.470
you get 0.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:03.740
So we only consider the
quadrature component,

00:35:03.740 --> 00:35:06.130
which is given by
the coherent state.

00:35:06.130 --> 00:35:07.600
This is a principle of homodyne.

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:09.556
You set your
quadrature component

00:35:09.556 --> 00:35:10.680
with your local oscillator.

00:35:17.210 --> 00:35:18.010
OK.

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:24.320
But now, I have a beam splitter.

00:35:24.320 --> 00:35:26.810
And the way you
can think about it

00:35:26.810 --> 00:35:30.270
is, you can get everything
in operator algebra,

00:35:30.270 --> 00:35:35.210
but just take my word or
follow the procedure now

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:37.200
that we are saying,
we can always

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:38.780
think about a
quantum field that it

00:35:38.780 --> 00:35:41.770
has an average value
and some fluctuations.

00:35:41.770 --> 00:35:44.300
And if you pass it through
an optical element or a beam

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:46.860
splitter, we have a
transmission coefficient,

00:35:46.860 --> 00:35:49.930
but it multiplies the
mean value of the field.

00:35:49.930 --> 00:35:53.580
But it also multiplies the
fluctuations of the field.

00:35:53.580 --> 00:35:57.860
So that's why I'm saying the
beam splitter is actually

00:35:57.860 --> 00:36:01.030
splitting the
fluctuations of the field.

00:36:01.030 --> 00:36:06.205
And therefore, you get reduced
fluctuations in either beam.

00:36:06.205 --> 00:36:09.680
But we have to consider
that there may be vacuum,

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:12.260
and the vacuum has
also some fluctuations

00:36:12.260 --> 00:36:16.025
and will reflect in or transmit
through parts of the vacuum.

00:36:22.720 --> 00:36:31.150
So now, we want to
understand photocurrents.

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:45.070
For photocurrents, we take those
quantities and square them.

00:36:48.430 --> 00:36:52.280
So which one should I take?

00:36:55.636 --> 00:36:57.610
Well, let me take
the first line.

00:36:57.610 --> 00:36:59.950
So this is i1.

00:36:59.950 --> 00:37:07.530
So if I calculate now i1, I
obtain t squared alpha squared,

00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:12.450
plus the cross product
between the first two terms

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:19.510
is 2 times t alpha
times t delta a1.

00:37:19.510 --> 00:37:22.340
And then, I get a second
term from the vacuum,

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:30.580
which is 2tr alpha delta b2.

00:37:30.580 --> 00:37:38.270
And let me assume that we have
a balanced beam splitter, 50-50.

00:37:38.270 --> 00:37:41.280
So t squared is simply 1/2.

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:44.970
Alpha squared is the
number of photons.

00:37:44.970 --> 00:37:46.190
So this term becomes n/2.

00:37:57.120 --> 00:37:58.500
t squared is 1/2.

00:37:58.500 --> 00:37:59.610
It cancels with the 2.

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:01.110
We are left with alpha.

00:38:01.110 --> 00:38:04.660
And this is shot noise.

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:07.510
Here, appears our square root n.

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:10.510
So you can say the
shot noise comes

00:38:10.510 --> 00:38:14.150
because we have homodyned
the quantum noise.

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:17.950
The quantum noise, which is the
same for all coherent states,

00:38:17.950 --> 00:38:20.082
has now been multiplied
with square root n

00:38:20.082 --> 00:38:21.290
through the homodyne process.

00:38:29.935 --> 00:38:30.435
OK.

00:38:34.120 --> 00:38:35.860
So I lost my line.

00:38:35.860 --> 00:38:38.620
That's delta a2.

00:38:38.620 --> 00:38:41.630
And then-- and
this is important--

00:38:41.630 --> 00:38:44.820
because of the mixing
at the beam splitter,

00:38:44.820 --> 00:38:49.160
the quantum noise off the
vacuum gets also homodyned

00:38:49.160 --> 00:38:50.560
by a factor of square root n.

00:38:55.270 --> 00:38:59.980
So now, I think you see
what I told you before.

00:38:59.980 --> 00:39:05.310
The transmitted beam has
half of its noise coming

00:39:05.310 --> 00:39:09.060
from the coherent state,
and half of the noise

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:13.570
comes from the vacuum.

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:15.750
So if I would now
take the current,

00:39:15.750 --> 00:39:18.140
square it, calculate
the variance,

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:22.650
I would find that I have n/2
photons with a variance of n/2.

00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:26.360
But an identical
contribution of the noise

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:28.950
will come from the
original coherent state

00:39:28.950 --> 00:39:30.840
and from the vacuum.

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:32.900
So therefore, when
I replace the vacuum

00:39:32.900 --> 00:39:38.760
by a strongly squeezed vacuum,
the beam, the current i1,

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:40.800
lost half of its shot noise.

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:43.930
We had n/2 photons
with a noise--

00:39:43.930 --> 00:39:45.530
with a variance, which was n/4.

00:39:48.087 --> 00:39:48.670
Any questions?

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:49.170
Yes.

