00:43:01.780 --> 00:43:06.170
but what happens is we have
a propagating laser beam.

00:43:06.170 --> 00:43:10.270
If you would simply move your
mirror by half a wavelength,

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:11.840
you get a minus sign.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:15.960
So eventually, all of the
phases-- the beam splitter

00:43:15.960 --> 00:43:18.880
phase, the propagating
phase-- all the phases

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:20.140
have to be controlled.

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:23.200
And in essence, what you do is
you put an experiment together,

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:25.705
you measure some noise, and
then you move your mirror

00:43:25.705 --> 00:43:27.070
or you change your phase.

00:43:27.070 --> 00:43:30.524
And then, you really figure out
which noise is now subtracting

00:43:30.524 --> 00:43:32.440
and which noise is
constructively interfering.

00:43:36.019 --> 00:43:36.685
Other questions?

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:40.630
OK.

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:43.060
But the other thing
is now obvious.

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:49.620
When we measure i1
minus i2, everything

00:43:49.620 --> 00:43:54.740
related to the coherent
input, to the original noise

00:43:54.740 --> 00:43:57.380
of the beam, cancels out.

00:43:57.380 --> 00:43:59.360
And what we are
measuring is only

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:02.420
the noise which came in
through the other part.

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:06.080
So this is the reason why, if
you have interesting light you

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:08.790
want to measure it, you
use a local oscillator.

00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:11.140
But then, you do i1 minus i2.

00:44:11.140 --> 00:44:14.570
And this is what I presented to
you at the end of last class,

00:44:14.570 --> 00:44:17.970
is the way how
people have measured

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:19.095
the signature of squeezing.

