01:05:27.520 --> 01:05:31.160
really act as conceptual
models for more complicated,

01:05:31.160 --> 01:05:33.940
more general things.

01:05:33.940 --> 01:05:36.370
So I've decided now,
over the last few years,

01:05:36.370 --> 01:05:38.530
to make quantum
information language

01:05:38.530 --> 01:05:42.370
an essential ingredient
of this course.

01:05:42.370 --> 01:05:44.770
But I should say over
the last couple of years,

01:05:44.770 --> 01:05:49.220
I've de-emphasized some of the
more formal algorithmic things,

01:05:49.220 --> 01:05:51.240
but I'm focusing
on the concepts.

01:05:51.240 --> 01:05:52.740
And I think some
concepts are really

01:05:52.740 --> 01:05:57.230
highlighted by using
quantum information aspects.

01:05:57.230 --> 01:05:59.170
So with that
introduction, we want

01:05:59.170 --> 01:06:02.360
to talk about single photons.

01:06:02.360 --> 01:06:10.060
And I want to introduce for
you the single photon qubit.

01:06:10.060 --> 01:06:15.610
Now, [INAUDIBLE] would think, if
you talk about single photons,

01:06:15.610 --> 01:06:18.850
you automatically
have one qubit.

01:06:18.850 --> 01:06:20.910
0 is no photon.

01:06:23.740 --> 01:06:25.740
One is the single photon state.

01:06:34.510 --> 01:06:37.120
We make in addition
later on, this

01:06:37.120 --> 01:06:39.740
is not the most
robust qubit, because

01:06:39.740 --> 01:06:43.110
if, due to unavoidable losses
or limited quantum efficiency,

01:06:43.110 --> 01:06:45.380
you have one photon,
and you lose it,

01:06:45.380 --> 01:06:47.970
you think the bit
has been flipped.

01:06:47.970 --> 01:06:49.900
So you don't want
to really use that,

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:55.376
but we will use, in a
moment, a single photon

01:06:55.376 --> 01:06:57.190
in two different quantum states.

01:06:57.190 --> 01:07:00.010
And then, if you detect zero,
you know you've lost it.

01:07:00.010 --> 01:07:03.520
We will talk about one photon,
which is either here or there.

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:06.260
And this is zero of
our qubit, and this

01:07:06.260 --> 01:07:07.750
would be one of our qubit.

01:07:07.750 --> 01:07:09.110
But we will come to that later.

01:07:09.110 --> 01:07:11.720
I first need the Hilbert
space of zero one

01:07:11.720 --> 01:07:14.120
to introduce a few
things, and then we'll

01:07:14.120 --> 01:07:23.930
use what we've learned to define
the dual-rail single photon

01:07:23.930 --> 01:07:26.050
state.

01:07:26.050 --> 01:07:28.985
But for now we don't have
to make this distinction.

01:07:31.775 --> 01:07:33.150
The question we
want to answer is

01:07:33.150 --> 01:07:42.940
what happens when
those states pass

01:07:42.940 --> 01:07:44.090
through optical components.

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:56.800
I want to show you how
beam splitters and phase

01:07:56.800 --> 01:08:01.940
shifters can be used-- very
simple optical components--

01:08:01.940 --> 01:08:05.690
they can be used to realize
an arbitrary single qubit

01:08:05.690 --> 01:08:08.040
operation.

01:08:08.040 --> 01:08:10.370
And then we introduce
non-linear interferometers,

01:08:10.370 --> 01:08:13.890
and we get two qubit operations.

01:08:13.890 --> 01:08:23.869
So let's start out very simple
and talk about phase shifters

01:08:23.869 --> 01:08:24.660
and beam splitters.

01:08:33.010 --> 01:08:34.779
And this is pretty
much how far we

01:08:34.779 --> 01:08:38.950
will get today in this chapter.

01:08:38.950 --> 01:08:52.399
Well, if you have a single
photon and time passes on,

01:08:52.399 --> 01:08:55.479
the single photon
gets phase shifted.

01:08:59.590 --> 01:09:19.706
If you pass it through
a dispersive medium,

01:09:19.706 --> 01:09:21.080
it will have
another phase shift.

01:09:24.200 --> 01:09:31.649
So this is how phase
shifts can be realized.

01:09:31.649 --> 01:09:35.950
But there is one caveat, and
that immediately tells us

01:09:35.950 --> 01:09:39.640
we can't get away with just
a single photon in one fiber

01:09:39.640 --> 01:09:42.140
and phase shifting it,
because everything phase

01:09:42.140 --> 01:09:43.040
shifts a photon.

01:09:43.040 --> 01:09:47.120
Time and everything which
is in the beam path.

01:09:47.120 --> 01:09:50.109
So whenever we talk about the
phase, we need a reference.

01:09:59.090 --> 01:10:02.220
So therefore, we're
immediately drawn

01:10:02.220 --> 01:10:06.720
that one mode and one
photon is not enough,

01:10:06.720 --> 01:10:09.216
even if you're interested
in one-photon gates,

01:10:09.216 --> 01:10:09.965
we need two modes.

01:10:15.340 --> 01:10:17.995
Just think about two wave
guides or two optical fibers.

01:10:21.810 --> 01:10:31.310
We call them mode A and B.
If you put one photon in--

01:10:31.310 --> 01:10:35.530
and this is now the symbol for
a phase shifter, a little box

01:10:35.530 --> 01:10:45.670
with the letter
phi-- then we get

01:10:45.670 --> 01:10:48.900
a phase shift of the state one.

01:10:48.900 --> 01:10:52.380
And the second mode A
acts as a reference mode

01:10:52.380 --> 01:10:55.050
to detect the shift
of phase, let's say

01:10:55.050 --> 01:10:58.590
by interfering the two photons.

01:10:58.590 --> 01:11:05.650
So in general, we
have an input state,

01:11:05.650 --> 01:11:08.580
and we obtain an output state,
which has a phase shift.

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:13.315
We'll come back to
phase shifters later.

01:11:28.230 --> 01:11:30.110
So we'll have two modes.

01:11:30.110 --> 01:11:36.220
The next thing we can do
is we can combine modes,

01:11:36.220 --> 01:11:38.850
and this is done
with a beam splitter.

01:11:38.850 --> 01:11:40.810
So we've talked
about beam splitters

01:11:40.810 --> 01:11:43.280
in the context of
homodyne detection.

01:11:43.280 --> 01:11:45.300
We've talked about
beams splitters most

01:11:45.300 --> 01:11:47.650
of the first hour with
a clicker question,

01:11:47.650 --> 01:11:51.590
and I was mainly referring
to the beam splitter

01:11:51.590 --> 01:11:54.000
before in a rather
non-formal way.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:58.720
If you've a 50:50 beam splitter,
and you have two inputs,

01:11:58.720 --> 01:12:01.230
you get a symmetric and
antisymmetric combination

01:12:01.230 --> 01:12:03.200
of the two, if it's a
50:50 beam splitter.

01:12:03.200 --> 01:12:04.790
What else can you get?

01:12:04.790 --> 01:12:10.410
Or, I used the concept of just
reflection and transmission

01:12:10.410 --> 01:12:11.240
coefficients.

01:12:11.240 --> 01:12:13.270
I think that's all important
to get an intuitive

01:12:13.270 --> 01:12:14.820
feel for the beam splitter.

01:12:14.820 --> 01:12:17.550
But now I use a more
rigorous approach.

01:12:17.550 --> 01:12:21.960
I have a beam splitter,
which is characterized

01:12:21.960 --> 01:12:22.955
by an angle theta.

01:12:25.830 --> 01:12:28.630
We will later find
out what theta is.

01:12:28.630 --> 01:12:35.060
And we have an input mode A
and a second input mode B,

01:12:35.060 --> 01:12:37.540
and those modes get mixed now.

01:12:37.540 --> 01:12:43.260
We have output modes B prime
and output modes A prime.

01:12:43.260 --> 01:12:47.360
And we can use the
Schrodinger picture

01:12:47.360 --> 01:12:50.270
and talk about the photon
states in those modes,

01:12:50.270 --> 01:12:52.790
but I prefer to use
the Heisenberg picture,

01:12:52.790 --> 01:12:55.770
so when I put A, A
prime, B and B prime in,

01:12:55.770 --> 01:12:59.760
just think about
annihilation operators which

01:12:59.760 --> 01:13:03.730
annihilate photons
in those modes.

01:13:03.730 --> 01:13:08.301
So what I postulate
is that this system

01:13:08.301 --> 01:13:10.050
is described by the
following Hamiltonian.

01:13:21.680 --> 01:13:24.450
And I'm sort of telling
you, this Hamiltonian

01:13:24.450 --> 01:13:26.500
describes this beam splitter.

01:13:26.500 --> 01:13:27.910
You will say, why and how?

01:13:27.910 --> 01:13:32.020
Well, I will tell you what this
Hamiltonian does to the modes,

01:13:32.020 --> 01:13:34.090
and then we have the
quantum description

01:13:34.090 --> 01:13:37.840
of the beams splitter, and you
will then see in your homework

01:13:37.840 --> 01:13:40.870
that this quantum description
of the beam splitter

01:13:40.870 --> 01:13:45.230
does exactly what it is expected
to do to coherent states.

01:13:45.230 --> 01:13:47.230
It just splits a
laser beam into two,

01:13:47.230 --> 01:13:49.800
with a reflection and
transmission coefficient

01:13:49.800 --> 01:13:53.510
which are cosine squared
theta and sine squared theta.

01:13:53.510 --> 01:13:57.120
And I will also show you that
this beam splitter is doing

01:13:57.120 --> 01:13:59.640
the same, splitting
with cosine squared

01:13:59.640 --> 01:14:03.210
and sine squared theta
probabilities, a single photon.

01:14:03.210 --> 01:14:05.760
So in essence, I give
you the Hamiltonian,

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:08.470
I discuss that the
transfer matrix, which

01:14:08.470 --> 01:14:12.670
is built upon this Hamiltonian,
does everything you ever

01:14:12.670 --> 01:14:15.460
wanted a beam splitter to do,
and therefore you can say,

01:14:15.460 --> 01:14:19.470
this defines the beam splitter.

01:14:19.470 --> 01:14:21.610
OK, if you have a
Hamiltonian, that

01:14:21.610 --> 01:14:30.990
means after propagating
through the Hamiltonian,

01:14:30.990 --> 01:14:33.810
we have the following transfer.

01:14:33.810 --> 01:14:38.170
You may be familiar with
putting the unitary time

01:14:38.170 --> 01:14:40.790
evolution here, and the
time which has elapsed,

01:14:40.790 --> 01:14:43.760
but we are always
using a fixed time

01:14:43.760 --> 01:14:46.300
after the light has
transformed the beam splitter.

01:14:46.300 --> 01:14:49.600
So you can see the
time t is absorbed

01:14:49.600 --> 01:14:55.830
in the definition of
h, the Hamiltonian,

01:14:55.830 --> 01:14:59.930
and b is really the unitary
time evolution from [? being ?]

01:14:59.930 --> 01:15:01.980
before and [? being ?]
after the beam splitter.

01:15:06.050 --> 01:15:09.740
So the transformation,
which transforms the modes

01:15:09.740 --> 01:15:15.070
at this beam splitter, has now
the following unitary operator.

01:15:20.540 --> 01:15:26.250
And we have modes a,
b, mode one and two,

01:15:26.250 --> 01:15:27.700
before the beam splitter.

01:15:27.700 --> 01:15:29.370
After the beam
splitter, they have

01:15:29.370 --> 01:15:32.680
been transformed to
a prime and b prime.

01:15:32.680 --> 01:15:37.840
And we obtain that by
taking the input modes

01:15:37.840 --> 01:15:40.910
and doing unitary
time evolution.

01:15:40.910 --> 01:15:44.930
You do simply the
operator transformation

01:15:44.930 --> 01:15:47.560
for unitary transformation.

01:15:47.560 --> 01:15:51.130
So we can now transform
the operators a and b.

01:15:57.130 --> 01:15:59.056
I'm not going with you
through the exercise

01:15:59.056 --> 01:16:00.305
how you transform an operator.

01:16:03.050 --> 01:16:06.740
I think in undergraduate
quantum mechanics classes,

01:16:06.740 --> 01:16:09.300
you do the
Baker-Campbell-Hausdorff

01:16:09.300 --> 01:16:14.680
formula, how to use with
operators in the exponent.

01:16:14.680 --> 01:16:19.560
And if you do with that,
you find-- not surprisingly,

01:16:19.560 --> 01:16:22.420
a beam splitter is a linear
element-- that what you get

01:16:22.420 --> 01:16:25.640
is a linear
combination of a and b.

01:16:45.760 --> 01:16:49.770
So if you don't like me
postulating an operator

01:16:49.770 --> 01:16:52.400
and saying, "Believe me,
this is a beam splitter,"

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:54.240
you can reverse engineer.

01:16:54.240 --> 01:16:58.020
You can say, this really looks
like the modes, the operators

01:16:58.020 --> 01:17:01.720
a b get linearly superposed
with cosine and sine.

01:17:01.720 --> 01:17:05.100
This is what a beam splitter
does, is it mixes two modes.

01:17:05.100 --> 01:17:07.320
And then you can reverse
engineer and figure out

01:17:07.320 --> 01:17:09.440
that it's exactly the
Hamiltonian above which

01:17:09.440 --> 01:17:09.940
does it.

01:17:12.520 --> 01:17:17.110
So your homework will show
that this happens exactly

01:17:17.110 --> 01:17:18.580
for coherent states.

01:17:18.580 --> 01:17:21.350
So if you've a coherent
state with alpha,

01:17:21.350 --> 01:17:24.545
you get a coherent state with
alpha cosine theta in one arm,

01:17:24.545 --> 01:17:27.020
and alpha sine theta
in the other arm,

01:17:27.020 --> 01:17:31.090
and you will see that
everything works beautifully.

01:17:31.090 --> 01:17:40.380
I have to use one convention
now for a 50:50 beam splitter.

01:17:40.380 --> 01:17:43.980
And I use a convention
that I chose theta

01:17:43.980 --> 01:17:48.670
to be pi over 2
b and 90 degrees.

01:17:48.670 --> 01:17:52.980
And we want to use
symbolic language,

01:17:52.980 --> 01:17:56.600
because we want to draw
diagrams of multiple beam

01:17:56.600 --> 01:17:58.630
splitters and such.

01:17:58.630 --> 01:18:10.130
So this tilted square is the
symbol for beam splitter.

01:18:10.130 --> 01:18:15.040
We have input ports a
and b on the left side.

01:18:15.040 --> 01:18:22.440
We have output ports, which
are now b prime and a prime.

01:18:22.440 --> 01:18:27.450
And for the 50:50 beam
splitter, the modes

01:18:27.450 --> 01:18:38.310
are symmetric and
antisymmetric superpositions.

01:18:38.310 --> 01:18:43.930
So this is the symbol for
the unitary transformation b.

01:18:43.930 --> 01:18:47.640
And since one output port has a
minus sign, it's antisymmetric,

01:18:47.640 --> 01:18:49.410
and one is positive.

01:18:49.410 --> 01:18:52.824
We usually put a dot there
which distinguishes the two

01:18:52.824 --> 01:18:53.490
different ports.

01:19:01.960 --> 01:19:05.020
So this is the operator B.

01:19:05.020 --> 01:19:10.840
We have already used, for
the unitary transformation,

01:19:10.840 --> 01:19:11.860
the operator b dagger.

01:19:22.350 --> 01:19:34.360
So for the operator b dagger,
using the equations above,

01:19:34.360 --> 01:19:38.140
we have input modes a
b, but what happens now

01:19:38.140 --> 01:19:42.290
is for the operator b
dagger, the output modes

01:19:42.290 --> 01:19:44.350
are interchanged.

01:19:44.350 --> 01:19:47.200
So we have a plus b over
square root a, a minus b

01:19:47.200 --> 01:19:50.680
over square root 2, and
therefore the symbol

01:19:50.680 --> 01:19:52.435
for b dagger has the dot here.

01:20:01.840 --> 01:20:10.150
I just want to warn you
that there are other phase

01:20:10.150 --> 01:20:13.670
conventions in the literature
which are equivalent.

01:20:13.670 --> 01:20:16.440
But sometimes if you read a
paper and all of the minus

01:20:16.440 --> 01:20:19.170
signs appear somewhere
else, well, people

01:20:19.170 --> 01:20:20.950
have a different
phase convention.

01:20:20.950 --> 01:20:27.190
You can postulate that
you have a beam splitter

01:20:27.190 --> 01:20:32.020
without having the i here.

01:20:32.020 --> 01:20:34.530
And everything works similarly.

01:20:34.530 --> 01:20:38.590
It's just that, for
instance, in this equation,

01:20:38.590 --> 01:20:40.640
you get an i here.

01:20:40.640 --> 01:20:43.900
So imaginary units
and plus-minus signs

01:20:43.900 --> 01:20:46.640
and that busyness are
phase conversations.

01:20:46.640 --> 01:20:48.850
If you'd say, hey, but if
you another definition,

01:20:48.850 --> 01:20:51.080
don't you have
another beam splitter?

01:20:51.080 --> 01:20:53.030
Yes, it is another
beam splitter,

01:20:53.030 --> 01:20:56.740
but I can always get it out
of my beam splitter-- which

01:20:56.740 --> 01:20:59.370
now is our beam splitter--
by putting a phase

01:20:59.370 --> 01:21:00.670
shifter afterwards.

01:21:00.670 --> 01:21:04.390
So it doesn't limit the
generality of the discussion

01:21:04.390 --> 01:21:08.200
by defining our beam
splitter in this way.

01:21:08.200 --> 01:21:09.520
OK, time is over.

